New song! “Wild Places” is out this morning on Spotify (or wherever you get your music). Link in bio. This is a song that went through a number of iterations and changes over the past five years. I wrote this version of the chorus with @johncraigie in mind and was super excited that he agreed to sing on it. I’m a long time fan of his music and was honored to collaborate with him. As well, we brought in two more of my favorite musicians @shooktwins to back him up with their signature angelic harmonies. Can’t thank ya’ll enough for your support on the song. You really brought the vision to life. “Wild Places” is a love letter to the natural world and our connection (or loss of connection) to it. I’d say this is the centric theme in most of my music but this song is perhaps the most direct with the messaging. It’s one of the most mellow songs on the record but also one of the songs that I felt exemplifies the direction of the album and the “folk hop” genre that I’m exploring. For whatever reason it felt like the right one to roll out first. I hope ya’ll enjoy it and if you do please give me a follow on Spotify and like the song if you’re feeling it, add it to a playlist, or share it with a friend! This helps me out big time with my future releases. Lots more singles will be rolling out over the coming months so standby for lots more new music… Much love to everyone who contributed on this track! @rudyslizewski @tapwatermusic @lockjaw43 @asherfulero @dominic.armstrong @redrocketsglare 🎬 @skiparmstrong Matt Baker

New song “Growing Up” is out today! Link to Spotify in bio. I collaborated with my friend @sapientkills on this song and it features both him and his kids on the chorus. A bit more background on the song and how it came to be:

The instrumental for “Growing Up” started as a piano sample that I had slowed down to half speed over a basic drum pattern. I wrote the hook and verses to that and then brought the track over to Sape. From there, he reworked the arrangement and created a totally fresh beat with a new piano part out of my original demo. I wrote the song on and off during my shoulder injuries which took me off the water for the better part of a year. Those injuries, along with life changes, triggered a feeling of introspection and thoughts surrounding the reality of aging. My biggest take away from this period was that much of what we perceive about aging is based on constructs created within our culture. We are told often by many - “you won’t always look as good or perform as well.” But if change is inevitable for all of us then what is the point of worrying about it? I couldn’t see it at the time, but my injuries were positive because I used that time to pursue my art and to work on getting strong again. I’ve seen a lot of athletes, professional or otherwise, give up on their passion out of fear that they will never be able to do it at the same level again. But ultimately, your mindset is so important when it comes to how you approach these inevitable ebbs and flows. At one point or another, change is coming for all of us. And while we may ultimately grow old and wear out - we certainly don’t have to grow up. Thanks for listening. ❤️🎶🙏 -Rush

I had a really fun @thelittlewhitesalmonrace this year! It was the year of the long boat with the new 12 ft @daggerkayaks “Vanguard” snagging 9 out of the top 10 spots. I raced my new @wakakayaks 9 ft “Gangsta"which I had a blast dialing in this past week. But I will likely transition to a long boat next year since it’s now been demonstrated as the only way of standing a fighting chance at this event (at least without a short boat category and with the water being on the low side). I admit that I’ve resisted the long boats for this race mainly because I feel that they’re a lot more dangerous. Especially as an event organizer in years past, the idea made me weary of enabling it on a course where safety is thin and hazards are high. But most importantly, I felt that long boats weren’t consistently being paddled on the Little White by the over arching community. If folks were paddling them regularly and practicing in them routinely I would have felt differently… But it seems now the time has come! In my opinion the “Vanguard” looks a lot safer and more fun to paddle than any of its long boat predecessors. Not to mention there being new and progressive designs like the Scorch X from @pyranha.kayaks at 10 ft long. But I think the question is, will these designs inspire other kayak companies to develop longer kayaks that implement modern rocker that are easier/safer to paddle? Will it also potentially pressure other races to change from a 9ft length limit to an open class? Dagger started the trend with the Green Boat designed specifically to win @greenrivernarrowsrace over a decade ago and most kayak companies followed suit with their own iterations. Overall I think this is really good for the progression of boat design and allows for more interesting options on the river. Ultimately racing is niche and I think the future is more likely to be shaped by what the general public has the most fun in. But it will be cool to see where it goes. Huge thanks to @darbymcadams @egthekilla @toddwellskayak and others for a great year! Best kayak race in the game! 🙌💯🌊 📸 @hayleymstuart

This last weekend would have been the @northforkchampionship Although the NFC has been canceled indefinitely, It's been awesome reading the outpour of love and support from the kayak community for this incredibly special event. What @byrdinand and @reganbyrd created was a massive leap for the sport of kayaking and arguably the most groundbreaking event the sport has ever seen. Ya'll deserve so much praise for the hard work and love you poured into making this thing go! I'll never forget the fear and excitement riding up in the bus to Jake's. The after parties at the Dirty Shame with  DJ Revolve. The amazing paddling. And most importantly the incredible community. I probably won't miss the hangovers while directing the media while also doing practice laps on a juicy Jacobs Ladder. That always felt like a lot. But I'm so glad I did it. It's safe to say we all grew from this event and it definitely elevated the sport and the caliber of whitewater that folks feel comfortable racing on. I’m thankful to have raced in 7/10 NFC’s and to have produced the media for 4 of them. It was a damn fun rally and thank you to everyone who made it all possible!!! ❤️❤️❤️ 📸 @johnjwebster @ Mike Leeds @tait_trautman

Lyrics video out today for “Take Them River.” Here’s a bit more background on how this song came to be. I first heard @lonesomepony playing this song on the Grand Canyon a couple of years back. He originally wrote it for his cousin who had passed away and was also an avid kayaker. The song connected with me and I asked if he’d be open to me writing my own verses and adding a few percussion elements to the beat. I was honored that Mark was open to the idea since it’s fundamentally his song performed by his amazing band Rapidgrass. For some context, Mark is both a professional musician and a professional skier. So the collaboration felt like it was a great fit for both of us. I wrote the verses for this version of the song with a number of friends in mind who I’ve lost to the river. Death in the river community has been a consistent presence in my life since I first started paddling at an early age and I’ve been conceptualizing a song like this for years. Losing friends to the river has given me a positive perspective on the fragility of life and the benefits of being grateful for every moment here. In other ways, I think it has desensitized me and at times has given me a darker outlook on the nature of kayaking and adventure sports in general. As my friend the late Hayden Kennedy stated, “climbing is either the greatest gift or a curse.” The same can be applied to kayaking. It is the most beautiful experience until it all too quickly isn’t. When I witness the pain that loss in the mountains takes on a mother, father, brother or sister it makes me question the whole endeavor. At the same time, I know for myself that I wouldn’t have this life any other way and I know that I’ll never stop loving and enjoying my time on the river and in the mountains. I don’t have the answers and I often don’t know what to say. But I hope the song resonates with anyone who has lost someone to the river, or otherwise. Thanks for listening.

Lost in the sauce of 1.6 million CFS on the Congo River. We snuck this rapid down a series of side channels but I suspect the main channel could be paddled? It’s definitely the biggest river feature I’ve ever seen. These rapids were all about avoiding the whirl pools and eddies which made biting off the main lines pretty sketchy. The few times we did find ourselves in the middle of this river were the scariest moments I’ve had in my kayak. On Nov 3rd at 11:45 PM we were hit at the epicenter of a 6.4 earthquake here in Nepal. We were on day three of paddling the Thuli Bheri River. I was fast asleep in our camp when I felt the earth moving beneath me. There was a loud bang and it felt as if a fist punched up through the earth, throwing me a foot or two off the ground. I couldn't find the zipper to my bivy bag and had to ride out the quake in a state of panic while screaming and trying to get out. It was undoubtedly the most terror I have ever felt in my life. Rock slides fell all through the canyon and the air became thick with dust as rubble moved through the gorge around us. If this had happened on any other night at any of our other campsites, I'm not sure we would have been as lucky. We're told that 100+ people died in the small town of Rimna just downstream and the numbers in the Jajarkot region are 150+ deceased and thousands homeless. The hotel our fixer Gopal was staying in collapsed and he was the only one out of seven to survive. Paddling out through the destruction on our way back to Nepal Gunj yesterday was a surreal experience. I feel incredibly lucky for having survived this and also a deep level of sadness for those who were less fortunate around us. The saddest part of all this is that it seems that these types of incidents often impact those who have the least. If you have any means, there is a link in my bio towards the relief effort. I've made the tough call to end my trip early and head home tomorrow. It’s been a hard decision but this has brought up a lot of emotions for me personally and I just don’t feel like I have a lot of juice left to squeeze at this point. Big thanks to my paddling crew @bennymrr + @gravyboat84 and huge thanks to @jetbutterflies @chand_rajiv @anupicepal and everyone else who supported us in this beautiful and special corner of the world. ❤️🌊🏔️🇳🇵

Despite the earthquake that ended our river trip, The Thuli Bheri River was an incredible experience. It is undoubtably one of the best sections of continuous whitewater I’ve ever paddled. And all the people we met along the way couldn’t have been friendlier. If you haven’t already, please consider donating something to the relief effort that will help some of the folks in need who call this river basin home. A little goes a long way and you can donate via the fundraiser to @blinknoworg at the link in my bio. Here’s a 📸 of me through one of the iconic rapids in Golden Canyon by @gravyboat84 ❤️🌊🏔️

The Thuli Bheri whitewater style is like this for over 100K. There is very little breathing room on this river and it is unbelievably continuous and quality paddling. It’s tough to give the river justice in photos because there are so many smaller rapids stacked on top of one another but not too many that stand out in the way that rapids do on some rivers. It’s commonly  described as a Grade IV river but we had healthy flows and I would say although most the moves are in the Grade IV category there’s still a ton of Class V mixed in and all of it is Class V consequences with how steep and continuous the whitewater is. Very NF Payette style in that regard. I could have done with a little less water myself to make some of the massive ledge holes smaller and some of the read and run a bit less hectic. Especially towards the second half of the trip the river was quite big with some solid gradient and gnarly features. But it lived up to all the hype and then some. A true classic among classics. As well, if you’ve been following my posts about the earthquake that hit on our final night on the river please see the link in my bio on how to help some of the folks who live in this river basin who have lost a lot from this tragic event. You can donate direct to @blinknoworg or check the link in my bio. Even a little can be helpful. 📸 @gravyboat84

“New Day” single featuring my buddy @vaughn.sims is out this morning, wherever you get your music. This feels like an appropriate song to release at the end of what has undoubtedly been one of the most formative years of my life. I traveled to Colombia, Mexico, and Nepal (twice). Each trip taught me something different and each journey was important for me in its own way. "New Day" is ultimately about suffering and the nature of impermanence. But it's also about the beauty that comes with change and the fact that no matter how hard things get, there is always a new horizon up ahead. It's about letting go of old patterns and embracing the new ones. In many ways, it sums up what this year has been for me. A year of loss, growth and transition. But we keep on moving.
